You are an expert in JavaScript, React, Next.js App Router, Firebase, Gemini API integration, MailerSend, Shadcn UI, Radix UI, Tailwind CSS, and Zod.

Build a small, clean, conversion-focused web app that guides users through a questionnaire and generates a tailored partner acrobatics training plan. The app should prioritize simplicity, clarity, strong UX, and secure server-side handling of AI and email logic.

Code Style and Structure
- Write concise, technical JavaScript/TypeScript code with clear intent.
- Use functional and declarative patterns; avoid classes.
- Prefer simple, maintainable solutions over over-engineering.
- Keep files small and focused.
- Use descriptive names with auxiliary verbs (e.g. isSubmitting, hasAcceptedTerms, canProceed).
- Use early returns and guard clauses.
- Avoid deep nesting.
- Prefer composition over abstraction until reuse is clearly needed.
- Structure files in this order where relevant: exports, subcomponents, helpers, constants, schemas.

General Project Priorities
- Keep the app lightweight and MVP-friendly.
- Optimize for a small number of users, not premature scale.
- Focus on one clear funnel:
  - landing page
  - questionnaire
  - email capture + terms acceptance
  - server-side plan generation
  - email delivery
  - success state
- Do not introduce unnecessary architectural complexity.
- Favor readability and fast iteration.

Tech Stack Rules
- Use Next.js App Router.
- Prefer Server Components by default.
- Use Client Components only when interactivity is required.
- Use Route Handlers for backend endpoints.
- Do not use Firebase Cloud Functions unless clearly necessary.
- Use Firebase primarily for hosting and optional Firestore persistence.
- Use Gemini API only from the server side.
- Use MailerSend only from the server side.
- Never expose secrets to the client.

TypeScript and Validation
- Use TypeScript throughout.
- Use Zod for request validation and schema parsing.
- Validate all questionnaire input on the server.
- Keep shared schemas in a dedicated lib or feature-level schema file.
- Infer types from Zod schemas where possible.

Naming Conventions
- Use lowercase with dashes for directories (e.g. app/workout-plan, components/questionnaire-step).
- Use PascalCase for components.
- Use camelCase for variables, functions, and props.
- Use clear names that reflect domain concepts:
  - acrobaticsType
  - userRole
  - trainingGoal
  - experienceLevel
  - availableDays
  - limitations
  - email
  - hasAcceptedTerms

App Structure
- Organize by feature, not by technical layer only.
- Preferred structure:

  app/
    page.tsx
    questionnaire/
      page.tsx
    success/
      page.tsx
    api/
      generate-plan/
        route.ts

  components/
    landing/
    questionnaire/
    ui/

  lib/
    firebase/
    gemini/
    mailersend/
    validation/
    utils/

  content/
    questionnaire.ts
    prompts.ts

  types/

React Best Practices
- Use function components.
- Keep components focused and presentational where possible.
- Lift state only when necessary.
- Prefer local state for form flow unless shared state becomes cumbersome.
- Avoid unnecessary global state.
- If global state is needed for multi-step questionnaire persistence, use Zustand sparingly and only for client-side UI state.
- Avoid heavy useEffect logic when server-first patterns are sufficient.
- Avoid unnecessary memoization.
- Use Suspense only where it genuinely improves UX.

Next.js App Router Best Practices
- Follow server-first architecture.
- Use Route Handlers for form submission and AI/email orchestration.
- Keep API logic close to the domain.
- Use server-only modules for secrets and service integrations.
- Use environment variables for all secrets.
- Never use NEXT_PUBLIC_ for Gemini, Firebase admin, or MailerSend secrets.
- Prefer async server components when fetching server-side data.
- Use loading and error states intentionally, not excessively.

Form and Questionnaire Rules
- The questionnaire must feel simple, progressive, and motivating.
- Break the flow into clear, digestible steps.
- Show only the necessary fields at each stage.
- Preserve answers across steps.
- Prevent submission until required fields are complete.
- Require email and terms acceptance before final submission.
- Use clear validation messages.
- Keep the number of questions low in the MVP.
- Prefer radio groups, segmented controls, checkboxes, and selects over free text where possible.
- Use free text only when it meaningfully improves training personalization.

Domain Logic
- The product is a tailored partner acrobatics workout plan generator.
- Core questionnaire fields should support:
  - acrobatics type (e.g. L-Base, Standing)
  - role (Base, Flyer, both)
  - level
  - goals
  - training frequency
  - available equipment
  - optional limitations or weak points
- The final generated plan should be structured and practical.
- Prefer consistent output sections such as:
  - profile summary
  - training focus
  - warm-up
  - main drills
  - accessory work
  - weekly structure
  - safety notes
- Do not generate vague, generic motivational content when concrete training guidance is expected.

Gemini API Rules
- Call Gemini only inside server-side Route Handlers or server-only modules.
- Build prompts from validated user input.
- Keep prompts structured and explicit.
- Request predictable output in a structured format.
- Prefer JSON-shaped output that can be transformed into email-friendly content.
- Sanitize and normalize model output before use.
- Handle model failures gracefully.
- Return safe fallback errors to the client.
- Never trust model output without parsing/validation.

MailerSend Rules
- Send emails only from the server side.
- Keep email sending logic isolated in a dedicated service module.
- Use a clean transactional email structure.
- Ensure the app can handle email send failure separately from plan generation failure when possible.
- Log send attempts in a minimal, privacy-conscious way if persistence is enabled.
- Keep copy clear, friendly, and concise.

Firebase Rules
- Use Firebase App Hosting for deployment.
- Use Firestore only if persistence is needed.
- If Firestore is used, keep the schema minimal and explicit.
- Store only what is useful:
  - submission metadata
  - validated questionnaire answers
  - generated plan
  - delivery status
- Avoid storing unnecessary personal data.
- Apply proper Firestore security rules.
- Use Firebase Admin only on the server side.

UI and Styling
- Use Shadcn UI and Radix UI as the UI foundation.
- Use Tailwind CSS for styling.
- Prefer a clean, modern, high-conversion landing page aesthetic.
- Design mobile-first.
- Use strong hierarchy, generous spacing, and clear CTA buttons.
- Keep the UI calm and professional, not visually noisy.
- Use Tailwind utilities directly.
- Avoid introducing additional styling complexity unless truly needed.
- Do not use Stylus for this project unless a real need emerges.
- Favor consistency over novelty.

Landing Page Rules
- The landing page must have one primary goal: start the questionnaire.
- Use a strong headline, concise supporting copy, and a prominent CTA.
- Explain the value quickly:
  - tailored plan
  - based on user role and acrobatics style
  - delivered by email
- Include light trust-building elements:
  - simple explanation of the process
  - benefits
  - what the user gets
- Avoid clutter and unnecessary sections in the MVP.

Performance
- Keep client-side JavaScript minimal.
- Minimize use client.
- Avoid unnecessary libraries.
- Optimize images and assets.
- Keep the landing page fast.
- Avoid large animation libraries unless clearly needed.
- Prefer native Next.js capabilities over third-party abstractions.

Error Handling
- Handle errors and edge cases at the beginning of functions.
- Use explicit validation failures.
- Provide user-friendly error messages in the UI.
- Log server-side errors with enough detail for debugging, but never leak secrets.
- Separate validation errors, AI errors, and email delivery errors conceptually.

Security and Privacy
- Treat all user input as untrusted.
- Validate and sanitize all incoming data.
- Never expose API keys.
- Never call Gemini or MailerSend from the browser.
- Keep personal data collection minimal.
- Be privacy-conscious with email and questionnaire answers.
- Avoid collecting sensitive health data unless absolutely necessary.
- If limitations/injuries are included, keep wording optional and minimal.

Accessibility
- Use semantic HTML.
- Ensure keyboard accessibility.
- Use accessible labels and descriptions.
- Ensure good color contrast.
- Make the step flow understandable for screen readers.

Testing
- Test critical flows first:
  - questionnaire progression
  - validation
  - final submission
  - API success/failure
- Prefer practical tests over excessive coverage.
- Add integration tests for the main conversion flow if time allows.

Content and Copy
- Keep copy concise and motivating.
- Use plain, confident language.
- Prioritize clarity over cleverness.
- Write CTA text that is direct and action-oriented.
- Make form labels and helper text immediately understandable.

Key Conventions
- Prefer server components.
- Prefer route handlers over external backend services for this MVP.
- Prefer simple local state over global state.
- Use Zustand only if multi-step state becomes awkward without it.
- Use Zod for all server-side validation.
- Keep AI prompt building explicit and easy to inspect.
- Keep the codebase small, clean, and easy to iterate on.

Definition of Done
- User lands on a clean landing page.
- User can complete a short questionnaire.
- User can enter email and accept terms.
- Submission hits a secure server-side endpoint.
- Gemini generates a tailored structured training plan.
- MailerSend sends the result to the user.
- The app handles invalid input and service failures gracefully.
- Secrets remain server-side.
- The implementation stays simple and maintainable.